I20061205-0800

package test;
public class E1 {
        public E1(String label) {}
        public E1() {
                String s= "foo";
                System.out.println(s);
                this(s);
                System.out.println(s);
        }
}

=> "s" in "this(s)" does not have a binding.
=> Expected: Binding for "s", like in "System.out.println(s)".

Fault-tolerance issue. When ill-positionned, the compiler doesn't resolve subparts of an explicit constructor call, e.g.

public class X {
	public X() {
		System.out.println();
		this(zork);
		Zork.this.this();
		<Zork>this();
	}
}

could diagnose all 'zork' issues.

Added GenericTypeTest#test1120.

When a model with a mixed-content Document Root gets serialized, trailing comments are not placed on a new line. Suppose we have a document consisting of a root element and a trailing comment:

    EPackage pkg = ExtendedMetaData.INSTANCE.demandPackage(null);
    XMLTypeDocumentRoot doc = (XMLTypeDocumentRoot) 
      EcoreUtil.create(ExtendedMetaData.INSTANCE.getDocumentRoot(pkg));
    doc.getMixed().add(
        ExtendedMetaData.INSTANCE.demandFeature(null, "root", true),
        XMLTypeFactory.eINSTANCE.createAnyType());
    doc.getMixed().add(XMLTypePackage.Literals.XML_TYPE_DOCUMENT_ROOT__COMMENT, "comment");
    Resource res = new XMLResourceImpl();
    res.getContents().add(doc);
    HashMap options = new HashMap();
    options.put(XMLResource.OPTION_EXTENDED_META_DATA, ExtendedMetaData.INSTANCE);
    options.put(XMLResource.OPTION_DECLARE_XML, Boolean.FALSE);
    res.save(System.out, options);

When saved, it would look like this:

<root/><!--comment-->

In method XMLString.addComment(String), I believe the intent was to add a LF before each trailing comment (i.e., one that appears after the root element). However, the if statement that checks if the comment is trailing returns false when a Document Root object is used as the model root:

    if (firstElementMark != null && elementNames.isEmpty())
    {
      addLine();
    }

The addLine() in this case never executes, because elementNames is not empty -- it contains a single null entry (which I believe stands for the Document Root).

It appears that changing the conditional like this fixes the problem:

    if (firstElementMark != null && (elementNames.isEmpty() || (elementNames.size() == 1 && elementNames.get(0) == null)))
    {
      addLine();
    }

The changed condition handles the original case as well as the case when a single null element is in elementNames.

Build ID: M20060921-0945

Steps To Reproduce:
1. Create a treeview to view a UML2 model with wrapper clases for the uml2 elements.

2. Create a problems view structure of problems corresponding to various wrapped uml2 elements contained within the UML2 model.

3. Create a goto for the problems view, so that when a problem is double clicked, it displays the file with the problem, the node in the outline view that contains the problem, and an editor form to edit the node with the problem.


More information:
I am creating a plugin the displays a uml2 model in an outline view, and every time u click on a node, it displays an editor form for the element clicked on to edit the properties associated with the element that is selected. I have created a the outline view, editor forms and a problems view. I have what seems to be a bug however when trying to open up the form, on a specific node in the outline view.

If the file, containing the model is closed, then no nodes have previously been expanded, when I call setSelection(ISelection selection, boolean reveal), it only opens the file after double clicking a problem from the problem view. If however, the node that corresponds to the problem view had previously appeared in the outline, and the model file is not opened, it does go direct to the node and opens the node in the form. In fact, once the node has been displayed in the outline view at all then I can repeatedly double click the problem and get straigh to it. This is what has led me to think that there is some sort of bug that is preventing me from getting to the node if it hasnt previously been displayed in the outline view.

This is the code example.

//PART 1 - Get the NodeId from the problems View

  /**
   * Goes to the node related to the marker.
   *
   * @param marker The resource marker.
   */
  public void gotoMarker(final IMarker marker) {
    // get info from the marker and go to this form.
    try {
      final String nodeId = (String) marker.getAttribute("whichNode");
      editorContentOutline.setSelected(nodeId);
    } catch (CoreException e) {
      if (kLog.isErrorEnabled()) {
        kLog.error(e);
      }
    }
  }


//PART 2 - Use the node to set the node as selected.

public void setSelected(final String nodeId) {

    final TreeItem[] items = getTreeViewer().getTree().getItems();
    WrappedUML2Object res = null;
    for (int i = items.length; --i >= 0;) {
      final TreeItem item = items[i];
      final WrappedUML2Object obj = (WrappedUML2Object) item
        .getData();
      if (!obj.getName().equals(nodeId)) {
        //find the object relating to the NodeId
        res = findItem(obj, nodeId);
        break;
      }
    }
    if (res != null) {
      // setSelection
      getTreeViewer().setSelection(new StructuredSelection(res), true);
    }
  }

//PART 2 - find method for getting a wrapped UML2 object.
  private WrappedUML2Object findItem(
    final WrappedUML2Object structuredObj, final String nodeId) {

    WrappedUML2Object result = null;
    if (result != null) {
      return result;
    }
    if (structuredObj.getName().equals(nodeId)) {
      return structuredObj;
    }
    final WrappedUML2Object[] children = structuredObj.getChildren();
    for (int i = children.length; --i >= 0;) {
      result = findItem(children[i], nodeId);
      if (result != null) {
        return result;
      }
    }
    return null;
  }
